description:
When using 1.1rc1, ajc (AspectJ compiler) does not behave correctly when compiling classes from a subpackage. This is a regression since rc1 and differs from the behavior of javac. I suspect that this issue may be related to a change in the underlying Eclipse compiler.

To reproduce the issue, follow these steps:
1. Create a class in a subpackage. For example:
   package subpackage;
   public class Test {
       public static void main(String[] args) {
           System.out.println("Hello");
       }
   }
2. Compile the class using the following command:
   ajc subpackage\Test.java

After executing the command, a directory named "subpackage" is created under the existing "subpackage" directory. The compiled Test.class file is placed in the subpackage\subpackage directory. As a result, running the java command leads to the following exception:

Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: subpackage/Test

To resolve this issue, you can use the following command instead:
ajc -d . subpackage\Test.java
This command correctly puts the compiled class in the expected directory structure.
